        "### Comparison of Results\n",
        "\n",
        "A comparison of the four approaches demonstrates the trade-offs between computational overhead and model accuracy. \n",
        "\n",
        "- Approach 1 (Lazy Fitting) and Approach 2 (Explicit Pre-Training) produce identical predictions because they both optimize the underlying tree-based estimators using default parameters (MAE ~5517). \n",
        "- Approach 3 (Optuna Tuned and Trained) explores the hyperparameter space efficiently using Optuna's Tree-structured Parzen Estimator (TPE), significantly improving the Mean Absolute Error (MAE ~3735) and corresponding Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE). \n",
        "- Approach 4 (SpotOptim Tuned and Trained) leverages the `spotoptim` surrogate model. In this limited evaluation, it provides a strong improvement over defaults (MAE ~5059). While Optuna slightly outperformed SpotOptim under this strict identical low-trial budget, it still strongly proves the effectiveness of automated spotoptim hyperparameters configurations safely enclosed inside the outer-shell orchestrator prior to prediction.\n",
        "\n",
        "The visualizations for each tuning approach (Approaches 3 and 4) demonstrate that the tuned models provide a more nuanced fit to both the diurnal cycles and broader load trends compared to Approaches 1 and 2.\n"
